ate=April 11, 2019|accessdate=April 15, 2019}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha|name=note_d}}{{refn|The Lynx traded this pick and their 2021 second round pick to Indiana for [[Shenise Johnson]] and the 16th pick.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fever.wnba.com/news/shenise-johnson-traded/|title=Fever Acquire Draft Picks in Trade with Minnesota|website=fever.wnba.com|publisher=WNBA|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha|name=note_l}}\n| [[Iowa Hawkeyes women's basketball|Iowa]]\n|-\n| 15\n| [[Leaonna Odom]]\n| {{USA}}\n| [[New York Liberty]]{{refn|group=lower-alpha|name=note_b}}{{refn|group=lower-alpha|name=note_n}}\n| [[Duke Blue Devils women's basketball|Duke]]\n|-\n| 16\n| [[Crystal Dangerfield]]\n| {{USA}}\n| [[Minnesota Lynx]]{{refn|group=lower-alpha|name=note_l}}\n| [[UConn Huskies women's basketball|UConn]]\n|-\n| 17\n| [[Brittany Brewer]]\n| {{USA}}\n| [[Atlanta Dream]]{{refn|As part of a three team deal, the Mercury traded this pick to Atlanta.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/wnba/story/_/id/28737240/mercury-acquire-jessica-breland-3-team-deal-dream-sun|title=Mercury acquire Jessica Breland in 3-team deal with Dream, Sun|website=espn.com|publisher=ESPN|first=Josh|last=Weinfuss|date=February 19, 2020|accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha|name=note_k}}\n| [[Texas Tech Lady Raiders basketball|Texas Tech]]\n|-\n| 18\n| [[Te'a Cooper]]\n| {{USA}}\n| [[Phoenix Mercury]]{{refn|The Lynx traded this pick to Phoenix for [[Stephanie Talbot]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mercury.wnba.com/news/mercury-acquire-2020-second-round-pick-from-minnesota/|title=Mercury Acquire 2020 Second-Round Pick From Minnesota|website=wnba.com|publisher=WNBA|date=May 21, 2019|accessdate=May 21, 2019}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha|name=note_e}}\n| [[Baylor Lady Bears basketball|Baylor]]\n|-\n| 19\n| [[Joyner Holmes]]\n| {{USA}}\n| [[Seattle Storm]]\n| [[Texas Longhorns women's basketball|Texas]]\n|-\n| 20\n| [[Beatrice Mompremier]]\n| {{USA}}\n| [[Los Angeles Sparks]]{{refn|The Sky traded this pick to Los Angeles for [[Jantel Lavender]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wnba.com/news/los-angeles-sparks-trade-jantel-lavender-to-chicago-sky/|title=Los Angeles Sparks Trade Jantel Lavender To Chicago Sky|website=wnba.com|publisher=WNBA|date=May 20, 2019|accessdate=May 20, 2019}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha|name=note_f}}\n| [[Miami Hurricanes women's basketball|Miami (FL)]]\n|-\n| 21\n| [[Luisa Geisels\u00f6der]]\n| {{GER}}\n| [[Dallas Wings]]\n| [[BG Donau-Ries|Donau-Ries]] <small>([[Damen-Basketball-Bundesliga|Germany]])</small>\n|-\n| 22\n| [[Leonie Fiebich]]\n| {{GER}}\n| [[Los Angeles Sparks]]\n| [[TSV 1880 Wasserburg|Wasserburg]] <small>([[Damen-Basketball-Bundesliga|Germany]])</small>\n|-\n| 23\n| [[Kaila Charles]]\n| {{USA}}\n| [[Connecticut Sun]]\n| [[Maryland Terrapins women's basketball|Maryland]]\n|-\n| 24\n| [[Jaylyn Agnew]]\n| {{USA}}\n| [[Washington Mystics]]\n| [[Creighton Bluejays women's basketball|Creighton]]\n|}\n\n===Third round===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! width=30|Pick\n! width=333|Player\n! width=200|Nationality\n! width=383|WNBA Team\n! width=333|School/Club Team/Country\n|-\n| 25\n| [[Mikayla Pivec]]\n| {{USA}}\n| [[Atlanta Dream]]\n| [[Oregon State Beavers women's basketball|Oregon State]]\n|-\n| 26\n| [[Erica Ogwumike]]\n| {{USA}}\n| [[New York Liberty]]\n| [[Rice Owls women's basketball|Rice]]\n|-\n| 27\n| [[Kobi Thornton]]\n| {{USA}}\n| [[Atlanta Dream]]{{refn|The Wings traded this pick to Atlanta for [[Imani McGee-Stafford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/sports/basketball/dream-trade-center-imani-mcgee-stafford-dallas/iZJSTdXdaRiLfAbs2qgG1K/|title=Dream trade center Imani McGee-Stafford to Dallas|work=Atlanta Journal Constitution|date=May 16, 2019|accessdate=May 17, 2019}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha|name=note_g}}\n| [[Clemson Tigers women's basketball|Clemson]]\n|-\n| 28\n| [[Kamiah Smalls]]\n| {{USA}}\n| [[Indiana Fever]]\n| [[James Madison Dukes women's basketball|James Madison]]\n|-\n| 29\n| [[Stella Johnson (basketball)|Stella Johnson]]\n| {{USA}}\n| [[Phoenix Mercury]]\n| [[Rider Broncs women's basketball|Rider]]\n|-\n| 30\n| [[Japreece Dean]]\n| {{USA}}\n| [[Chicago Sky]]{{refn|The Lynx traded this pick to Chicago for [[Alaina Coates]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sky.wnba.com/news/sky-acquire-2020-third-round-pick-from-minnesota-lynx/|title=Sky Acquire 2020 Third-Round Pick From Minnesota Lynx|website=wnba.com|publisher=WNBA|date=May 21, 2019|accessdate=May 21, 2019}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha|name=note_h}}\n| [[UCLA Bruins women's basketball|UCLA]]\n|-\n| 31\n| [[Haley Gorecki]]\n| {{USA}}\n| [[Seattle Storm]]\n| [[Duke Blue Devils women's basketball|Duke]]\n|-\n| 32\n| [[Kiah Gillespie]]\n| {{USA}}\n| [[Chicago Sky]]\n| [[Florida State Seminoles women's basketball|Florida State]]\n|-\n| 33\n| [[Lauren Manis]]\n| {{USA}}\n| [[Las Vegas Aces]]\n| [[Holy Cross Crusaders women's basketball|Holy Cross]]\n|-\n| 34\n| [[Tynice Martin]]\n| {{USA}}\n| [[Los Angeles Sparks]]\n| [[West Virginia Mountaineers women's basketball|West Virginia]]\n|-\n| 35\n| [[Juicy Landrum]]\n| {{USA}}\n| [[Connecticut Sun]]\n| [[Baylor Lady Bears basketball|Baylor]]\n|-\n| 36\n| [[Sug Sutton]]\n| {{USA}}\n| [[Washington Mystics]]\n| [[Texas Longhorns women's basketball|Texas]]\n|}\n\n== Footnotes ==\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2020 WNBA draft}}\n{{WNBA Drafts}}\n\n[[Category:Women's National Basketball Association Draft]]\n[[Category:April 2020 sports events in the United States|WNBA draft]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports|WNBA draft]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox sports draft\n| league        = WNBA\n| teams         = 12\n| name          = 2020 WNBA Draft\n| image         =\n| imagesize     =\n| caption       =\n| sport         = Basketball\n| date          = April 17, 2020\n| location      = Digital\n| network       = USA: [[WNBA on ESPN|ESPN]]<br>Canada: [[TSN2]]/[[Sportsnet One|SN1]]\n| first = [[Sabrina Ionescu]]<br>[[New York Liberty]]\n| prev = [[2019 WNBA draft|2019]]\n| next = [[2021 WNBA draft|2021]]\n}}\n\nThe '''2020 WNBA draft''' was the [[WNBA|league]]'s draft for the [[2020 WNBA season]]. A draft lottery was held on September 17, 2019 and the [[New York Liberty]] were awarded the first overall pick in the draft.<ref name=\"lottery\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wnba.com/news/wnba-draft-lottery-presented-by-state-farm-to-take-place-on-sept-17-on-espn2/|title=WNBA Draft Lottery Presented By State Farm To Take Place on Sept. 17 on ESPN2|website=wnba.com|date=September 12, 2019|accessdate=September 12, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"draw\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wnba.com/news/new-york-liberty-wins-top-pick-in-2020-wnba-draft-presented-by-state-farm/|title=New York Liberty Win Top Pick In WNBA Draft 2020 Presented By State Farm\u00ae|website=wnba.com|publisher=WNBA|date=September 17, 2019|accessdate=September 17, 2019}}</ref> Due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]] the draft was held virtually without players, guests, and the media on-site.  The draft was televised as planned.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wnba.com/news/wnba-draft-2020-to-be-held-april-17/|title=WNBA Draft 2020 Presented By State Farm To Be Held As Scheduled On April 17|publisher=WNBA|website=wnba.com|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Draft lottery==\n\nThe lottery selection to determine the order of the top four picks in the 2020 Draft took place during halftime of the [[2019 Connecticut Sun season|Connecticut Sun's]] semifinal game against the [[2019 Los Angeles Sparks season|Los Angeles Sparks]] on September 17, 2019 and was televised on [[WNBA on ESPN|ESPN2]].  Four non-playoff teams qualified for the lottery drawing: [[Indiana Fever]], [[Dallas Wings]], [[New York Liberty]], and [[Atlanta Dream]].<ref name=\"lottery\"/>\n\n===Lottery chances===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center; width: 70%\"\n! Team\n! Combined 2018\u20132019 Record\n! Lottery Chances (out of 1,000)\n|-\n| '''[[New York Liberty]]''' \u2013 WON\n| '''17\u201351'''\n| '''442'''\n|-\n| [[Indiana Fever]]\n| 19\u201349\n| 276\n|-\n| [[Dallas Wings]]\n| 25\u201343\n| 178\n|-\n| [[Atlanta Dream]]\n| 31\u201337\n| 104\n|}\n\nThe lottery odds were based on combined records from the 2018 and 2019 WNBA seasons. In the drawing, 14 balls numbered 1\u201314 are placed in a lottery machine and mixed. Four balls are drawn to determine a four-digit combination (only 11\u201312\u201313\u201314 is ignored & redrawn). The team assigned that four-ball combination receives the No. 1 pick.  The four balls are then placed back into the machine and the process is repeated to determine the second pick. The two teams whose numerical combinations do not come up in the lottery will select in the inverse order of their two-year cumulative record. [[Ernst & Young]] knows the discreet results before they're announced.<ref name=\"lottery\"/>\n\nThe order of selection for the remainder of the first round as well as the second and third rounds is determined by inverse order of the teams\u2019 respective regular-season records solely from 2019.<ref name=\"lottery\"/>\n\nThe lottery was won by the [[New York Liberty]], who had the best chance to win the lottery.  The [[Dallas Wings]] were awarded the second pick, followed by the [[Indiana Fever]] and finally the [[Atlanta Dream]].<ref name=\"draw\"/>\n\n==Eligibility==\nUnder the current [[collective bargaining agreement]] (CBA) between the WNBA and its players union, draft eligibility for players not defined as \"international\" requires the following to be true:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wnbpa.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/WNBA-WNBPA-CBA-2020-2027.pdf |title=Article XIII, Section 1: Player Eligibility |work=2020 Women's National Basketball Association Collective Bargaining Agreement |pages=110\u201311 |publisher=Women's National Basketball Players Association |accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n* The player's 22nd birthday falls during the calendar year of the draft. For this draft, the cutoff birth date is December 31, 1998.\n* She has either:\n** completed her college eligibility;\n** received a bachelor's degree, or is scheduled to receive such in the 3 months following the draft; or\n** is at least 4 years removed from high school graduation.\n\nA player who is scheduled to receive her bachelor's degree within 3 months of the draft date, and is younger than the cutoff age, is only eligible if the calendar year of the draft is no earlier than the fourth after her high school graduation.\n\nPlayers with remaining college eligibility who meet the cutoff age must notify the WNBA headquarters of their intent to enter the draft no later than 10 days before the draft date, and must renounce any remaining college eligibility to do so. A separate notification timetable is provided for players involved in postseason tournaments (most notably the [[NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|NCAA Division I tournament]]); those players must declare for the draft within 24 hours of their final game. The latter timetable proved to be moot due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|coronavirus]]-induced cancellation of the [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|2020 NCAA Tournament]].\n\n\"International players\" are defined as those for whom all of the following is true:\n* Born and currently residing outside the U.S.\n* Never \"exercised intercollegiate basketball eligibility\" in the U.S.\n\nFor \"international players\", the eligibility age is 20, also measured on December 31 of the year of the draft.\n\nThree players with remaining college eligibility, all of whom were juniors in the 2019\u201320 college season, declared for the draft:\n* [[Satou Sabally]] of [[Oregon Ducks women's basketball|Oregon]] announced on February 20 that she would enter the draft upon the end of Oregon's 2019\u201320 season. Although a [[Germany|German]] citizen, she falls under the rules for U.S. players not only because of playing at Oregon, but also via her birth in [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.espn.com/womens-college-basketball/story/_/id/28743871/oregon-junior-satou-sabally-enter-wnba-draft-season |title=Oregon junior Satou Sabally to enter WNBA draft after season |first=Holly |last=Rowe |authorlink=Holly Rowe |website=ESPN.com |date=February 20, 2020 |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Megan Walker]] of [[UConn Huskies women's basketball|UConn]] declared on March 14, after the cancellation of the NCAA tournament.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.yahoo.com/sports/uconns-walker-forgo-senior-enter-wnba-draft-182122819--ncaaw.html |title=UConn's Walker to forgo senior year, enter WNBA draft |agency=Associated Press |website=Yahoo Sports |date=March 14, 2020 |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Chennedy Carter]] of [[Texas A&M Aggies women's basketball|Texas A&M]] declared on March 29.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.espn.com/wnba/story/_/id/28968887/texas-star-chennedy-carter-declares-wnba-draft |title=Texas A&M star Chennedy Carter declares for WNBA draft |first=Mechelle |last=Voepel |website=ESPN.com |date=March 29, 2020 |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Draft==\n===Honorary picks===\nThe WNBA honored Alyssa Altobelli, Payton Chester, and Gianna Bryant, daughter of [[Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame|Hall of Fame]] basketball player [[Kobe Bryant]], who all died in the [[2020 Calabasas helicopter crash]], with honorary draft picks.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gianna Bryant, Alyssa Altobelli, Payton Chester selected as honorary picks at WNBA draft |url=https://www.espn.com/wnba/story/_/id/29050684/gianna-bryant-alyssa-altobelli-payton-chester-honorary-picks-wnba-draft |website=ESPN.com}}</ref>\n\n===First round===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! width=30|Pick\n! width=333|Player\n! width=200|